---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'In Memoriam';

const img1 = (await import('../../../assets/images/obras/in-memoriam/in-memoriam-01.jpg')).default;
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="In Memoriam — Work"
  description="In Memoriam (2001). Ephemeral sculpture — ice, glass, water, 300kg, 20 hours. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 003</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2001 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Ephemeral sculpture — ice, glass, water &nbsp;/&nbsp; 300 kg, 20 hours</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <img src={img1.src} alt="In Memoriam — Doric ice column dissolving in water urn, 2001" loading="eager">
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: In Memoriam — Column mid-dissolution, water rising ]</div>
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio:16/10;">[ Pending: In Memoriam — Final state, water and remnants ]</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            A 300-kilogram ice column dissolving slowly in water over twenty hours inside
            a glass container. The work captures the passage of time as irreversible material
            loss. As the ice melts, the solid mass transforms into the very liquid that
            surrounds and eventually replaces it — a process that is at once predictable
            and deeply affecting.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            <em>In Memoriam</em> operates as a meditation on impermanence and the
            impossibility of preservation. The glass container makes the process entirely
            visible — the viewer witnesses a slow disappearance in real time. The title
            invokes the language of commemoration, yet the work itself enacts the opposite:
            not the fixing of memory but its dissolution.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The ephemeral nature of the sculpture — existing fully only at the moment of
            its inauguration and progressively ceasing to exist — places temporality at
            the center of the work. What remains at the end is not the sculpture but its
            trace: water, the memory of a form, and the experience of having witnessed
            its passing.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            <em>In Memoriam</em> belongs to a lineage of works in which Escallon engages
            with materials undergoing transformation — processes of decay, dissolution, and
            disappearance that would become central to her practice. The work anticipates
            later explorations of time-based material processes, such as <em>Precipitacion
            de Arenas</em> and <em>Dispositivos para Ver Pasar el Tiempo</em>.
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>In Memoriam</strong><br>
            2001<br><br>
            Ephemeral sculpture.<br>
            Ice, glass, water.<br><br>
            300 kg<br>
            Duration: 20 hours
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            [ Pending exhibition data ]
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2001). <em>In Memoriam</em>.
            Ephemeral sculpture. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/in-memoriam/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>

<style>
  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    }
</style>
